{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20982527-monstrul-colombre-i-alte-cincizeci-de-povestiri", "title": "Monstrul Colombre \u0219i alte cincizeci de povestiri", "titleComplete": "Monstrul Colombre \u0219i alte cincizeci de povestiri", "description": "\u00centr-o zi, Stefano \u00ee\u0219i urmeaz\u0103 tat\u0103l pe mare. La un moment, vede \u00een dep\u0103rtare \u201eun lucru\u201c care le urm\u0103re\u0219te corabia. Afl\u0103 mai apoi c\u0103 doar el \u0219i \u201ecei de acela\u0219i s\u00e2nge\u201c \u00eel pot vedea, c\u0103 lucrul \u00eentunecat din zare este de fapt un monstru, un colombre ce-l va urm\u0103ri toat\u0103 via\u021ba, \u0219i c\u0103 \u00een cele din urm\u0103 \u00eel va ucide. Fermecat de g\u00e2ndul monstrului, Stefano \u00ee\u0219i dedic\u0103 via\u021ba m\u0103rii \u0219i-\u0219i tr\u0103ie\u0219te fericirea \u0219i bog\u0103\u021bia sub semnul mor\u021bii. Ajuns \u00een pragul sf\u00e2r\u0219itului, se hot\u0103r\u0103\u0219te s\u0103 \u00eenfrunte hidoasa creatur\u0103: aceasta-l ajunge din urm\u0103, dar, \u00een loc s\u0103-l ucid\u0103, \u00eei dezv\u0103luie de ce l-a urm\u0103rit toat\u0103 via\u021ba...", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1414341615i/20982527.jpg", "genres": ["Italian Literature", "Italy", "France", "School", "Short Stories", "Fantasy", "Roman", "Literature", "Classics", "Fiction"], "asin": "9734642405", "isbn": "9734642405", "isbn13": "9789734642403", "publisher": "Editura Polirom", "author": ["Dino Buzzati", "Mara Chiri\u0163escu", "Florin Chiri\u0163escu"], "publishDate": 1383289200000, "ratingHistogram": [31, 108, 457, 825, 698], "ratingsCount": 2119, "reviewsCount": 142, "numPages": 324, "language": "Romanian"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/449407.Pens_es", "title": "Pens\u00e9es", "titleComplete": "Pens\u00e9es", "description": "Blaise Pascal, the precociously brilliant contemporary of Descartes, was a gifted mathematician and physicist, but it is his unfinished apologia for the Christian religion upon which his reputation now rests. The Pense\u00e9s is a collection of philosohical fragments, notes and essays in which Pascal explores the contradictions of human nature in pscyhological, social, metaphysical and - above all - theological terms. Mankind emerges from Pascal's analysis as a wretched and desolate creature within an impersonal universe, but who can be transformed through faith in God's grace.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1393735440i/449407.jpg", "genres": ["France", "French Literature", "Christian", "17th Century", "Theology", "Christianity", "Religion", "Classics", "Philosophy", "Nonfiction"], "isbn": "0140446451", "publisher": "Penguin Classics", "author": ["A.J. Krailsheimer", "George Iancu Ghidu", "Blaise Pascal", "T.S. Eliot"], "publishDate": 806828400000, "ratingHistogram": [280, 917, 2928, 4406, 4889], "ratingsCount": 13420, "reviewsCount": 673, "numPages": 334, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1772910.White_Nights", "title": "White Nights", "titleComplete": "White Nights", "description": "White Nights is a short story by Fyodor Dostoevsky that was published in 1848. Set in St. Petersburg, it is the story of a young man fighting his inner restlessness. A light and tender narrative, it delves into the torment and guilt of unrequited love. Both protagonists suffer from a deep sense of alienation that initially brings them together. A blend of romanticism and realism, the story appeals gently to the senses and feelings.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1450699039i/1772910.jpg", "genres": ["Russia", "Novels", "Short Stories", "19th Century", "Romance", "Literature", "Audiobook", "Classics", "Fiction", "Russian Literature"], "author": ["Olga Shartse", "Fyodor Dostoevsky"], "publishDate": -3849955200000, "characters": ["Nastenka"], "places": ["St. Petersburg", "Russia"], "ratingHistogram": [1527, 6207, 28327, 55318, 51830], "ratingsCount": 143209, "reviewsCount": 14490, "numPages": 82, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/434903.The_Rings_of_Saturn", "title": "The Rings of Saturn", "titleComplete": "The Rings of Saturn", "description": "The Rings of Saturn \u2014 with its curious archive of photographs \u2014 records a walking tour along the east coast of England. A few of the things which cross the path and mind of its narrator (who both is and is not Sebald) are lonely eccentrics, Sir Thomas Browne's skull, a matchstick model of the Temple of Jerusalem, recession-hit seaside towns, wooded hills, Joseph Conrad, Rembrandt's \"Anatomy Lesson,\" the natural history of the herring, the massive bombings of WWII, the dowager empress Tzu Hsi, and the silk industry in Norwich.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1642038157i/434903.jpg", "genres": ["Fiction", "Essays", "Literary Fiction", "Novels", "German Literature", "Literature", "Travel", "Classics", "Germany", "20th Century"], "asin": "0811214133", "isbn": "0811214133", "isbn13": "9780811214131", "publisher": "New Directions", "author": ["Michael Hulse", "W.G. Sebald"], "publishDate": 922953600000, "characters": ["Joseph Conrad"], "places": ["East Anglia, England"], "ratingHistogram": [222, 567, 2051, 4739, 7309], "ratingsCount": 14888, "reviewsCount": 1671, "numPages": 296, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "Los Angeles Times Book Prize", "awardedAt": 883641600000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Prix du Meilleur Livre \u00c9tranger", "awardedAt": 915177600000, "category": "Essai", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Helen and Kurt Wolff Translator's Prize", "awardedAt": 915177600000, "category": "Michael Hulse", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "Dublin Literary Award", "awardedAt": 946713600000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7624.Lord_of_the_Flies", "title": "Lord of the Flies", "titleComplete": "Lord of the Flies", "description": "At the dawn of the next world war, a plane crashes on an uncharted island, stranding a group of schoolboys. At first, with no adult supervision, their freedom is something to celebrate; this far from civilization the boys can do anything they want. Anything. They attempt to forge their own society, failing, however, in the face of terror, sin and evil. And as order collapses, as strange howls echo in the night, as terror begins its reign, the hope of adventure seems as far from reality as the hope of being rescued. Labeled a parable, an allegory, a myth, a morality tale, a parody, a political treatise, even a vision of the apocalypse, Lord of the Flies is perhaps our most memorable novel about \u201cthe end of innocence, the darkness of man\u2019s heart.\u201d", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327869409i/7624.jpg", "genres": ["High School", "School", "Novels", "Dystopia", "Literature", "Adventure", "Classics", "Young Adult", "Fiction", "Read For School"], "asin": "0140283331", "isbn": "0140283331", "isbn13": "9780140283334", "publisher": "Penguin Books ", "author": ["William Golding"], "publishDate": 938761200000, "characters": ["Simon", "Ralph", "Piggy", "Roger", "Jack Merridew"], "ratingHistogram": [147282, 260534, 714669, 975448, 792758], "ratingsCount": 2890691, "reviewsCount": 55410, "numPages": 182, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/75579.Report_to_Greco", "title": "Report to Greco", "titleComplete": "Report to Greco", "description": "Kazantzakis's autobiographical novel 'Report to Greco' was one of the last things he wrote before he died. It paints a vivid picture of his childhood in Crete, still occupied by the Turks, and then steadily grows into a spiritual quest that takes him to Italy, Jerusalem, Paris, Vienna, Berlin, Russia and the Caucasus, and finally back to Crete again. At different times Nietzsche, Bergson, Buddha, Homer and Christ dominate as his spiritual masters.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1324520628i/75579.jpg", "genres": ["Fiction", "Greece", "Novels", "Religion", "Literature", "Travel", "Classics", "Biography Memoir", "Philosophy", "20th Century"], "asin": "0671220276", "isbn": "0671220276", "isbn13": "9780671220273", "publisher": "Touchstone", "author": ["Nikos Kazantzakis"], "publishDate": 177318000000, "ratingHistogram": [44, 101, 466, 1223, 2025], "ratingsCount": 3859, "reviewsCount": 421, "numPages": 611, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24013720-wind-pinball", "title": "Wind/Pinball: Two Novels", "titleComplete": "Wind/Pinball: Two Novels", "description": "Discover Haruki Murakami's first two novels.'If you're the sort of guy who raids the refrigerators of silent kitchens at three o'clock in the morning, you can only write accordingly.That's who I am.'Hear the Wind Sing and Pinball, 1973 are Haruki Murakami's earliest novels. They follow the fortunes of the narrator and his friend, known only by his nickname, the Rat. In Hear the Wind Sing the narrator is home from college on his summer break. He spends his time drinking beer and smoking in J's Bar with the Rat, listening to the radio, thinking about writing and the women he has slept with, and pursuing a relationship with a girl with nine fingers.Three years later, in Pinball, 1973, he has moved to Tokyo to work as a translator and live with indistinguishable twin girls, but the Rat has remained behind, despite his efforts to leave both the town and his girlfriend. The narrator finds himself haunted by memories of his own doomed relationship but also, more bizarrely, by his short-lived obsession with playing pinball in J's Bar. This sends him on a quest to find the exact model of pinball machine he had enjoyed playing years earlier: the three-flipper Spaceship.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1439382798i/24013720.jpg", "genres": ["Magical Realism", "Asian Literature", "Asia", "Literary Fiction", "Novels", "Japan", "Literature", "Japanese Literature", "Fiction", "Contemporary"], "asin": "0385352123", "isbn": "0385352123", "isbn13": "9780385352123", "publisher": "Knopf", "series": ["The Rat"], "author": ["Haruki Murakami", "Ted Goossen"], "publishDate": 1438671600000, "places": ["Japan"], "ratingHistogram": [385, 2680, 11685, 10702, 4199], "ratingsCount": 29651, "reviewsCount": 2965, "numPages": 234, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40961230-the-travelling-cat-chronicles", "title": "The Travelling Cat Chronicles", "titleComplete": "The Travelling Cat Chronicles", "description": "\n  Sometimes you have to leave behind everything you know to find the place you truly belong...\nNana the cat is on a road trip. He is not sure where he's going or why, but it means that he gets to sit in the front seat of a silver van with his beloved owner, Satoru. Side by side, they cruise around Japan through the changing seasons, visiting Satoru's old friends. He meets Yoshimine, the brusque and unsentimental farmer for whom cats are just ratters; Sugi and Chikako, the warm-hearted couple who run a pet-friendly B&amp;B; and Kosuke, the mournful husband whose cat-loving wife has just left him. There's even a very special dog who forces Nana to reassess his disdain for the canine species. But what is the purpose of this road trip? And why is everyone so interested in Nana? Nana does not know and Satoru won't say. But when Nana finally works it out, his small heart will break...", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1532711745i/40961230.jpg", "genres": ["Asia", "Fiction", "Cats", "Literary Fiction", "Adult", "Japan", "Audiobook", "Japanese Literature", "Animals", "Contemporary"], "asin": "B07BJLCTMK", "isbn": "0735235244", "isbn13": "9780735235243", "publisher": "Viking", "author": ["Philip Gabriel", "Hiro Arikawa"], "publishDate": 1540278000000, "ratingHistogram": [337, 1595, 8816, 23805, 37148], "ratingsCount": 71701, "reviewsCount": 12974, "numPages": 281, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "\u5c71\u7530\u98a8\u592a\u90ce\u8cde", "awardedAt": 1357027200000, "category": "", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/32586.Mysteries", "title": "Mysteries", "titleComplete": "Mysteries", "description": "In a Norwegian coastal town, society's carefully woven threads begin to unravel when an unsettling stranger named Johan Nagel arrives. With an often brutal insight into human nature, Nagel draws out the townsfolk, exposing their darkest instincts and suppressed desires. At once arrogant and unassuming, righteous and depraved, Nagel's bizarre behavior and feverish rants seduces the entire community even as he turns it on its head\u2014before disappearing as suddenly as he had arrived.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1391925208i/32586.jpg", "genres": ["Psychology", "Literary Fiction", "Mystery", "Novels", "19th Century", "Nobel Prize", "Scandinavian Literature", "Literature", "Classics", "Fiction"], "asin": "0374530297", "isbn13": "9780374530297", "publisher": "Farrar, Straus and Giroux", "author": ["Isaac Bashevis Singer", "Knut Hamsun", "Sven Birkerts", "Gerry Bothmer"], "publishDate": 1155020400000, "characters": ["Johan Nagel"], "places": ["Norway"], "ratingHistogram": [110, 409, 1365, 2690, 2815], "ratingsCount": 7389, "reviewsCount": 586, "numPages": 348}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/73480.The_Pledge", "title": "The Pledge", "titleComplete": "The Pledge", "description": "Set in a small town in Switzerland, The Pledge centers around the murder of a young girl and the detective who promises the victim\u2019s mother he will find the perpetrator. After deciding the wrong man has been arrested for the crime, the detective lays a trap for the real killer\u2014with all the patience of a master fisherman. But cruel turns of plot conspire to make him pay dearly for his pledge. Here Friedrich D\u00fcrrenmatt conveys his brilliant ear for dialogue and a devastating sense of timing and suspense. Joel Agee\u2019s skilled translation effectively captures the various voices in the original, as well as its chilling conclusion.One of D\u00fcrrenmatt\u2019s most diabolically imagined and constructed novels, The Pledge was adapted for the screen in 2000 in a film directed by Sean Penn and starring Jack Nicholson.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1328873113i/73480.jpg", "genres": ["Crime", "Mystery", "Novels", "School", "German Literature", "Thriller", "Literature", "Classics", "Fiction", "20th Century"], "asin": "0226174379", "isbn": "0226174379", "isbn13": "9780226174372", "publisher": "University of Chicago Press", "author": ["Friedrich D\u00fcrrenmatt", "Joel Agee"], "publishDate": 1159686000000, "places": ["Switzerland"], "ratingHistogram": [100, 457, 2007, 3675, 2399], "ratingsCount": 8638, "reviewsCount": 853, "numPages": 176, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17716.Waiting_for_Godot", "title": "Waiting for Godot", "titleComplete": "Waiting for Godot", "description": "The story revolves around two seemingly homeless men simply waiting for someone\u2014or something\u2014named Godot. Vladimir and Estragon wait near a tree, inhabiting a drama spun of their own consciousness. The result is a comical wordplay of poetry, dreamscapes, and nonsense, which has been interpreted as mankind\u2019s inexhaustible search for meaning. Beckett\u2019s language pioneered an expressionistic minimalism that captured the existential post-World War II Europe. His play remains one of the most magical and beautiful allegories of our time.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1327910301i/17716.jpg", "genres": ["Plays", "Philosophy", "France", "School", "Irish Literature", "Literature", "Theatre", "Classics", "Drama", "Fiction"], "publisher": "Grove", "author": ["Samuel Beckett"], "publishDate": 1293868800000, "characters": ["Estragon", "boy", "Vladimir (Samuel Beckett)", "Pozzo", "Lucky"], "ratingHistogram": [7938, 16244, 43299, 65489, 67547], "ratingsCount": 200517, "reviewsCount": 8732, "numPages": 109, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/19380.Candide", "title": "Candide", "titleComplete": "Candide", "description": "Candide is the story of a gentle man who, though pummeled and slapped in every direction by fate, clings desperately to the belief that he lives in \"the best of all possible worlds.\" On the surface a witty, bantering tale, this eighteenth-century classic is actually a savage, satiric thrust at the philosophical optimism that proclaims that all disaster and human suffering is part of a benevolent cosmic plan. Fast, funny, often outrageous, the French philosopher's immortal narrative takes Candide around the world to discover that -- contrary to the teachings of his distinguished tutor Dr. Pangloss -- all is not always for the best. Alive with wit, brilliance, and graceful storytelling, Candide has become Voltaire's most celebrated work.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1345060082i/19380.jpg", "genres": ["18th Century", "Fiction", "France", "French Literature", "School", "Novels", "Literature", "Classics", "Humor", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0486266893", "isbn": "0486266893", "isbn13": "9780486266893", "publisher": "Dover Publications, Incorporated", "author": ["Rockwell Kent", "Don Hagen", "Voltaire", "Sara Gioacchino Corcos", "Walter Jerrold"], "publishDate": 662716800000, "characters": ["Cunegonde", "Dr. Pangloss", "Pangloss", "Candide (Voltaire)"], "places": ["Argentina", "Suriname", "Romania", "Istanbul", "Constantinople", "Buenos Aires", "Turkey", "England", "Lisbon", "Transylvania", "Portugal", "Germany", "Netherlands", "Paraguay"], "ratingHistogram": [7958, 22614, 72527, 95977, 76088], "ratingsCount": 275164, "reviewsCount": 11468, "numPages": 129, "language": "English"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/123933.No_Exit", "title": "No Exit", "titleComplete": "No Exit", "description": "Jean-Paul Sartre, the great French existentialist, displays his mastery of drama in NO EXIT, an unforgettable portrayal of hell.The play is a depiction of the afterlife in which three deceased characters are punished by being locked into a room together for all eternity. It is the source of Sartre's especially famous and often misinterpreted quotation \"L'enfer, c'est les autres\" or \"Hell is other people\", a reference to Sartre's ideas about the Look and the perpetual ontological struggle of being caused to see oneself as an object in the world of another consciousness.", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1362639118i/123933.jpg", "genres": ["Fiction", "France", "Theatre", "French Literature", "School", "Literature", "Plays", "Classics", "Drama", "Philosophy"], "asin": "0573613052", "isbn": "0573613052", "isbn13": "9780573613050", "publisher": "Samuel French, Inc.", "author": ["Jean-Paul Sartre"], "publishDate": -378662400000, "characters": ["In\u00e8s", "Estelle", "Garcin"], "places": ["Hell"], "ratingHistogram": [562, 1457, 6441, 14769, 15765], "ratingsCount": 38994, "reviewsCount": 2244, "numPages": 60, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "New York Drama Critics' Circle Award", "awardedAt": -725817600000, "category": "Best Foreign Play", "hasWon": null}]}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28251250-white-noise", "title": "White Noise", "titleComplete": "White Noise", "description": "The National Book Award-winning classic from the author of Underworld and Libra, now a Netflix film starring Adam Driver, Don Cheadle, and Greta GerwigWhite Noise tells the story of Jack Gladney, his fourth wife, Babette, and four ultra\u00admodern offspring as they navigate the rocky passages of family life to the background babble of brand-name consumerism. When an industrial accident unleashes an \"airborne toxic event,\" a lethal black chemical cloud floats over their lives. The menacing cloud is a more urgent and visible version of the \"white noise\" engulfing the Gladneys\u2014radio transmissions, sirens, microwaves, ultrasonic appliances, and TV murmurings\u2014pulsing with life, yet suggesting something ominous.Part of the Penguin Orange Collection, a limited-run series of twelve influential and beloved American classics in a bold series design offering a modern take on the iconic Penguin paperbackWinner of the 2016 AIGA + Design Observer 50 Books | 50 Covers competition", "imageUrl": "https://images-na.ssl-images-amazon.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1476807953i/28251250.jpg", "genres": ["Literary Fiction", "Science Fiction", "Novels", "The United States Of America", "Literature", "Classics", "American", "Fiction", "20th Century", "Contemporary"], "asin": "0143129554", "isbn": "0143129554", "isbn13": "9780143129554", "publisher": "Penguin Classics", "author": ["Don DeLillo"], "publishDate": 1476774000000, "characters": ["Babette Gladney", "Dana Breedlove", "Jack Gladney", "Tweedy Browner"], "ratingHistogram": [2981, 8648, 25308, 41811, 35791], "ratingsCount": 114539, "reviewsCount": 8177, "numPages": 320, "language": "English", "awards": [{"name": "National Book Award", "awardedAt": 473414400000, "category": "Fiction", "hasWon": null}, {"name": "National Book Critics Circle Award", "awardedAt": 47341